# CarValuator Scraper Starter

This is a thesis-friendly starter project for collecting used-car listing data from:

- `autovit.ro`
- `mobile.de`

The goal is to build a dataset you can later use for price-fairness analysis:

- fair price
- suspiciously low price
- overpriced

## Important note

Both sites can change structure and anti-bot rules over time. On `mobile.de`, direct automated access is already protected more aggressively than `autovit.ro`, so this starter uses two different approaches:

- `autovit.ro`: parse the page's embedded JSON data
- `mobile.de`: use Playwright and extract rendered listing cards when access is allowed

Always review each website's terms, robots rules, and legal constraints before large-scale scraping.

## Setup

```powershell
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
python -m pip install -e .
python -m playwright install chromium
```

## Quick start

Scrape the first 3 Autovit search pages:

```powershell
car-scraper scrape-search autovit "https://www.autovit.ro/autoturisme" --pages 3 --output data\autovit_search.jsonl
```

Scrape a larger Autovit dataset:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli scrape-search autovit "https://www.autovit.ro/autoturisme" --pages 60 --delay 0.75 --output data\autovit_large.jsonl
```

Scrape one Autovit listing detail page:

```powershell
car-scraper scrape-detail autovit "https://www.autovit.ro/autoturisme/anunt/bmw-seria-1-ID7HNlbE.html"
```

Try a `mobile.de` search page:

```powershell
car-scraper scrape-search mobilede "https://suchen.mobile.de/auto/bmw-535-2014.html" --pages 1 --headful --browser-channel msedge --output data\mobilede_search.jsonl
```

Normalize and deduplicate one or more raw JSONL files:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli normalize data\autovit_search.jsonl --output data\training_ready.jsonl --report data\training_ready_report.json
```

If you want the pipeline to also collapse very likely near-duplicates:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli normalize data\autovit_search.jsonl data\mobilede_search.jsonl --output data\training_ready.jsonl --drop-fuzzy-duplicates
```

Export a training CSV from raw JSONL:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli export-csv data\autovit_large.jsonl --output data\autovit_large.csv --drop-fuzzy-duplicates --report data\autovit_large_export_report.json
```

Train baseline regressors and generate plots:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli train-models data\autovit_large.csv --output-dir data\model_results
```

Tune significance-based feature filtering during training:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli train-models data\autovit_large.csv --output-dir data\model_results --feature-selection-alpha 0.05 --min-pearson 0.05 --min-cramers-v 0.25
```

Train on `log1p(price_eur)` instead of raw price:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli train-models data\autovit_large.csv --output-dir data\model_results_log --log-target
```

Predict one Autovit listing with the trained model bundle:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli predict-from-link autovit "https://www.autovit.ro/autoturisme/anunt/bmw-seria-1-ID7HNlbE.html" --model-bundle data\model_results_log\best_model.joblib
```

Use a stricter or looser verdict threshold:

```powershell
python -m carvaluator_scraper.cli predict-from-link autovit "https://www.autovit.ro/autoturisme/anunt/bmw-seria-1-ID7HNlbE.html" --model-bundle data\model_results_log\best_model.joblib --threshold-percent 10
```

Start the local API for the future web app:

```powershell
$env:CARVALUATOR_MODEL_BUNDLE = "data\model_results_log\best_model.joblib"
carvaluator-api
```

Or with `uvicorn` directly:

```powershell
$env:CARVALUATOR_MODEL_BUNDLE = "data\model_results_log\best_model.joblib"
python -m uvicorn carvaluator_scraper.api:app --reload
```

Example request:

```powershell
Invoke-RestMethod -Method Post -Uri "http://127.0.0.1:8000/predict" -ContentType "application/json" -Body '{"site":"autovit","url":"https://www.autovit.ro/autoturisme/anunt/bmw-seria-1-ID7HNlbE.html","threshold_percent":15}'
```

Useful API routes:

- `GET /`
- `GET /health`
- `POST /predict`

The root route now serves a simple browser UI where you can paste an Autovit link and inspect the prediction visually.

## Output schema

Each output row is JSON with fields like:

- `source`
- `listing_id`
- `url`
- `title`
- `make`
- `model`
- `version`
- `price_value`
- `currency`
- `price_indicator`
- `seller_name`
- `seller_type`
- `location_city`
- `location_region`
- `year`
- `first_registration`
- `mileage_km`
- `fuel_type`
- `transmission`
- `power_hp`
- `engine_capacity_cm3`
- `body_type`
- `description`
- `raw`

`raw` keeps site-specific source data so you can revisit fields later without re-scraping immediately.

The normalized output adds model-ready fields such as:

- `price_eur`
- `market_price_label`
- `fuel_type`
- `transmission`
- `seller_type`
- `dedupe_exact_key`
- `dedupe_fuzzy_key`
- `completeness_score`

The training command generates:

- `metrics.csv`
- `training_report.json`
- `feature_significance.csv`
- `best_model.joblib`
- held-out prediction CSV files for each model
- `price_distribution.png`
- `price_vs_mileage.png`
- `correlation_heatmap.png`
- `actual_vs_predicted.png`

The `predict-from-link` command returns:

- the detected listing price
- the model's predicted fair price
- the percentage delta
- a verdict: `fair`, `too_low_suspicious`, or `too_high`
- the normalized features sent into the model

## mobile.de note

`mobile.de` now uses a more realistic Edge browser profile in the scraper, but the site still has active anti-bot protection and may block this environment.

If that happens, try:

- `--headful`
- `--browser-channel msedge`
- a normal residential connection
- rerunning from your own machine instead of a cloud or shared environment

## How this helps your thesis

A good early pipeline is:

1. Scrape listings into JSONL.
2. Normalize brand, model, year, mileage, fuel, gearbox, power, price.
3. Remove duplicates.
4. Train a regression model to predict expected price.
5. Convert the prediction error into labels like fair / too low / too high.

The current project now covers:

1. scraping
2. normalization and deduplication
3. CSV export for model training
4. baseline price-regression training
5. single-link price verdict inference for Autovit
6. a small FastAPI backend for frontend integration
